LATIN 1.description: Lecture, three hours; discussion, two hours. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 1.title: Elementary Latin

LATIN 100.description: Lecture, three hours. Enforced requisite: course 20 (may be taken concurrently). Introduction to developing skills of reading longer, continuous passages of original Latin prose and/or poetry texts, with attention to literary and cultural background. Course is requisite to advanced reading courses. May be repeated for credit twice with change of assigned readings and with consent of instructor. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 100.title: Intermediate Latin: Introduction to Reading Latin

LATIN 101.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 101.title: Plautus

LATIN 102.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 102.title: Terence

LATIN 103.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 103.title: Lucretius

LATIN 104.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 104.title: Ovid

LATIN 105A.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Reading of one or more books from first half of "Aeneid," designed especially for students with only limited experience in reading Latin poetry. May be repeated for credit with change in readings and consent of instructor. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 105A.title: Beginning Vergil: Selections from Aeneid I-VI

LATIN 105B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 105A. Reading and discussion of Vergil's "Eclogues," "Georgics," and/or second half of "Aeneid." May be repeated for credit with change in readings. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 105B.title: Advanced Vergil

LATIN 106.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 106.title: Catullus

LATIN 107.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 107.title: Horace

LATIN 108.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Selections from Catullus, Tibullus, and Propertius. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 108.title: Roman Elegy

LATIN 109.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Readings from author(s) of Roman satire, including Horace, Persius, and Juvenal, or related satiric texts. May be repeated for credit with change in readings and consent of instructor. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 109.title: Roman Satire

LATIN 110.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Work in sight reading and grammatical analysis of classical prose texts; writing of classical prose. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 110.title: Study of Latin Prose

LATIN 111.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 111.title: Livy

LATIN 112.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 112.title: Tacitus

LATIN 113.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 113.title: Cicero: Orations

LATIN 114.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 114.title: Roman Epistolography: Cicero and Pliny

LATIN 115.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 115.title: Caesar

LATIN 116.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Reading and discussion of either Petronius' "Satyricon" or Apuleius' "Metamorphoses" and development of genre of prose novel in antiquity. May be repeated for credit with change in author and text. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 116.title: Roman Novel

LATIN 117.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 117.title: Sallust

LATIN 118.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Selection of Seneca's works read in Latin. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 118.title: Seneca

LATIN 119A.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Readings of selected Roman prose author(s). Topics may vary from year to year and may be organized in terms of chronology (Republican or imperial), literary genre (Roman biography, antiquarian learning, or science), and/or theme. May be repeated for credit with topic change. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 119A.title: Readings in Roman Prose

LATIN 119B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Readings of selected Roman poetry author(s). Topics may vary from year to year and may be organized in terms of chronology (Republican or imperial), epic, lyric, elegy, and/or theme. May be repeated for credit with topic change. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 119B.title: Readings in Roman Poetry

LATIN 120.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 3. Reading of selected chapters of St. Jerome's translation of Bible, with emphasis on unclassical features of Latin. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 120.title: Vulgate

LATIN 121.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 100. Reading and discussion of one or more Latin patristic texts (especially works of Ambrose, Augustine, and/or Jerome), with emphasis on specific features of patristic, as opposed to classical, Latin. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 121.title: Patristic Texts

LATIN 130.description: Lecture, three hours. Basic competence in classical Latin required. Readings in postclassical Latin. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 130.title: Introduction to Postclassical Latin

LATIN 131.description: Lecture, three hours. Advanced readings of selected texts in postclassical Latin prose. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 131.title: Postclassical Latin Prose

LATIN 133.description: Lecture, three hours. Advanced readings of selected texts in postclassical Latin poetry. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 133.title: Postclassical Latin Poetry

LATIN 14.description: Lecture, 10 hours. Declensions of nouns and adjectives, conjugations in indicative mood, and primary uses of subjunctive mood. Emphasis on development of ability to read easy selections of classical prose. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 14.title: Elementary Latin: Intensive

LATIN 16.description: Lecture, 19 hours. Eight-week intensive introduction to Latin language equivalent to courses 1, 2, and 3. Offered in summer only. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 16.title: Intensive First-Year Latin

LATIN 189.description: Seminar, three hours. Limited to 20 students. Designed as adjunct to undergraduate lecture course. Exploration of topics in greater depth through supplemental readings, papers, or other activities and led by lecture course instructor. May be applied toward honors credit for eligible students. Honors content noted on transcript. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 189.title: Advanced Honors Seminars

LATIN 189HC.description: Tutorial, three hours. Limited to students in College Honors Program. Designed as adjunct to upper division lecture course. Individual study with lecture course instructor to explore topics in greater depth through supplemental readings, papers, or other activities. May be repeated for maximum of 4 units. Individual honors contract required. Honors content noted on transcript. Letter grading.
LATIN 189HC.title: Honors Contracts

LATIN 19.description: Seminar, one hour. Discussion of and critical thinking about topics of current intellectual importance, taught by faculty members in their areas of expertise and illuminating many paths of discovery at UCLA. P/NP grading.
LATIN 19.title: Fiat Lux Freshman Seminars

LATIN 197.description: Tutorial, two hours. Limited to juniors/seniors. Individual intensive study, with scheduled meetings to be arranged between faculty member and student. Assigned reading and tangible evidence of mastery of subject matter required. May be repeated for credit. Individual contract required. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 197.title: Individual Studies in Latin

LATIN 199.description: Tutorial, two hours. Limited to juniors/seniors. Supervised individual research or investigation under guidance of faculty mentor. Culminating paper or project required. May be repeated for credit. Individual contract required. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 199.title: Directed Research in Latin

LATIN 1G.description: Lecture, eight hours. Concurrently scheduled with course 14. No grading.
LATIN 1G.title: Elementary Latin for Graduate Students

LATIN 2.description: Lecture, three hours; discussion, two hours. Enforced requisite: course 1. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 2.title: Elementary Latin

LATIN 20.description: Lecture, three hours; discussion, one hour (when scheduled). Requisite: course 3 or 16. Formal review of Latin grammar and syntax and development of skills in reading original texts of Latin prose. Readings selected to introduce literature and culture of ancient Rome. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 20.title: Elementary Latin: Comprehensive Review

LATIN 200A.description: Lecture, three hours. Lectures on history of Latin literature, supplemented by reading of Latin texts in original language. May be taken independently for credit. S/U or letter grading.
LATIN 200A.title: History of Latin Literature

LATIN 200B.description: Lecture, three hours. Lectures on history of Latin literature, supplemented by reading of Latin texts in original language. May be taken independently for credit. S/U or letter grading.
LATIN 200B.title: History of Latin Literature

LATIN 200C.description: Lecture, three hours. Lectures on history of Latin literature, supplemented by reading of Latin texts in original language. May be taken independently for credit. S/U or letter grading.
LATIN 200C.title: History of Latin Literature

LATIN 201.description: Seminar, three hours. Close study of one epic poet other than Vergil (e.g., Ennius, Lucan, Valerius Flaccus, Statius, Silius Italicus), with attention to literary tradition of epic. May be repeated for credit with topic change. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 201.title: Roman Epic Tradition

LATIN 202.description: Seminar, three hours. Detailed consideration of entire Catullan corpus. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 202.title: Seminar: Catullus

LATIN 203A.description: Lecture, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 203A.title: Elegiac Poetry

LATIN 203B.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 203A is not requisite to 203B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 203B.title: Propertius

LATIN 204A.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 204A is requisite to 204B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 204A.title: Vergil's Aeneid

LATIN 204B.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 204A. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 204B.title: Vergil's Aeneid

LATIN 205A.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 205A.title: Seminar: Vergil's Bucolics

LATIN 205B.description: Seminar, three hours. Course 205A is not requisite to 205B. Close reading of Vergil's text; careful evaluation of influential criticism on poem, much of it recent; examination of work's place within tradition of rural poetry. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 205B.title: Seminar: Vergil's Georgics

LATIN 206.description: Lecture, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 206.title: Horace

LATIN 207.description: Seminar, three hours. Survey of history of Roman comedy. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 207.title: Roman Comedy

LATIN 208.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 208.title: Ovid

LATIN 209.description: Seminar, three hours. Detailed study of one individual satirist, with attention to his position in development of satirical genre in Roman literature. Choice of author varies from year to year. Close study of text, of characteristics of writer as social critic and artist, and of contemporary literary and social environment. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 209.title: Seminar: Roman Satire

LATIN 210.description: Lecture, three hours. Requisite: course 110. S/U or letter grading.
LATIN 210.title: Advanced Latin Prose Composition

LATIN 211A.description: Seminar, three hours. Study of considerable portions of writings of Sallust. May be taken independently for credit. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 211A.title: Seminar: Roman Historians -- Sallust

LATIN 211B.description: Seminar, three hours. Study of considerable portions of writings of Livy. May be taken independently for credit. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 211B.title: Seminar: Roman Historians -- Livy

LATIN 211C.description: Seminar, three hours. Study of considerable portions of writings of Tacitus. May be taken independently for credit. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 211C.title: Seminar: Romans Historians -- Tacitus

LATIN 214.description: Seminar, three hours. Study of biography in ancient Rome. Literary survey or focused readings on lives of Cornelius Nepos, Suetonius, Tacitus, or imperial chroniclers of 4th century C.E. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 214.title: Ancient Biography: Roman Lives

LATIN 215.description: Seminar, three hours. Works such as Petronius' "Satyricon" and Apuleius' "Metamorphoses:" study of literary problems. May be repeated for credit with topic change. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 215.title: Seminar: Roman Novel

LATIN 216.description: Seminar, three hours. Close study of one rhetorical text (e.g., "Rhetorica ad Herennium," Cicero's "de Oratore," Seneca's "Controversiae" or "Suasoriae," Quintilian's "Institutio"), with attention to its place in rhetorical tradition. May be repeated for credit with topic change. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 216.title: Roman Rhetoric

LATIN 220.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 220.title: Cicero's Orations

LATIN 221A.description: Lecture, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 221A.title: Cicero's Philosophical Works

LATIN 221B.description: Lecture, three hours. Course 221A is not requisite to 221B. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 221B.title: Cicero: De Natura Deorum

LATIN 222.description: Seminar, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 222.title: Seminar: Roman Stoicism

LATIN 223.description: Lecture, three hours. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 223.title: Lucretius

LATIN 224.description: Seminar, three hours. Detailed study of one work of prose or poetry by younger Seneca. May be repeated for credit with topic change. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 224.title: Seneca

LATIN 229.description: Seminar, three hours. Preparation: graduate-level knowledge of Latin. Practice in translation of previously unseen texts from variety of authors and genres. Topics include peculiarities of style and vocabulary of distinct genres, literary versus scholarly translation, semantic properties of particular words and constructions. S/U grading.
LATIN 229.title: Sight Translation

LATIN 231A.description: Seminar, three hours. Preparation: at least one upper division Latin course. Course 231A is not requisite to 231B. Studies in various areas of language and literature of medieval Latin. May be repeated for credit with consent of instructor. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 231A.title: Seminar: Medieval Latin

LATIN 231B.description: Seminar, three hours. Preparation: at least one upper division Latin course. Course 231A is not requisite to 231B. Studies in various areas of language and literature of medieval Latin. May be repeated for credit with consent of instructor. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 231B.title: Seminar: Medieval Latin

LATIN 232.description: Lecture, three hours. History and characteristics of popular Latin; its development into early forms of Romance languages. S/U or letter grading.
LATIN 232.title: Vulgar Latin

LATIN 235.description: Seminar, three hours. Close study, with attention to literary and historical background, of work of one or several poets who flourished between death of Ovid and fall of Roman Empire. May be repeated for credit with change in author. S/U or letter grading.
LATIN 235.title: Late Latin Poetry

LATIN 236.description: Seminar, three hours. Close study, with attention to literary and historical background, of work of one or several prose authors who flourished between death of Tacitus and fall of Roman Empire. May be repeated for credit with change in author. S/U or letter grading.
LATIN 236.title: Late Latin Prose

LATIN 240.description: Lecture, three hours. Development of Latin from earliest monuments until its emergence in Romance languages. S/U or letter grading.
LATIN 240.title: History of Latin Language

LATIN 242.description: Lecture, three hours. Linguistic situation in early Italy. Readings in Oscan, Umbrian, and early Latin texts. Latin grammar in context of Italic and Indo-European linguistics. S/U or letter grading.
LATIN 242.title: Italic Dialects and Latin Historical Grammar

LATIN 243.description: Seminar, three hours. Studies in development of book hand in Latin manuscripts earlier than invention of printing. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 243.title: Seminar: Latin Palaeography

LATIN 245.description: Seminar, three hours. Preparation: at least two upper division Latin courses. Requisite: course 100. Survey of texts by one or more authors from Renaissance to present, written on related topics. S/U or letter grading.
LATIN 245.title: Neo-Latin

LATIN 250.description: Seminar, three hours. Advanced study of some aspect of Latin language or literature or Roman culture. May be repeated for credit with topic change. S/U (2-unit course) or letter (4-unit course) grading.
LATIN 250.title: Topical Studies of Ancient Rome

LATIN 3.description: Lecture, three hours; discussion, two hours. Enforced requisite: course 2 or 14. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 3.title: Elementary Latin

LATIN 495.description: Seminar, to be arranged. Preparation: appointment as teaching assistant. Methodology of instruction in conjunction with classroom practice. May be repeated for credit. S/U grading.
LATIN 495.title: College Teaching of Latin

LATIN 596.description: Tutorial, to be arranged. S/U grading.
LATIN 596.title: Directed Individual Study or Research

LATIN 597.description: Tutorial, to be arranged. S/U grading.
LATIN 597.title: Study for M.A

LATIN 599.description: Tutorial, to be arranged. S/U grading.
LATIN 599.title: Research for Ph.D

LATIN 89.description: Seminar, three hours. Limited to 20 students. Designed as adjunct to lower division lecture course. Exploration of topics in greater depth through supplemental readings, papers, or other activities and led by lecture course instructor. May be applied toward honors credit for eligible students. Honors content noted on transcript. P/NP or letter grading.
LATIN 89.title: Honors Seminars

LATIN 89HC.description: Tutorial, three hours. Limited to students in College Honors Program. Designed as adjunct to lower division lecture course. Individual study with lecture course instructor to explore topics in greater depth through supplemental readings, papers, or other activities. May be repeated for maximum of 4 units. Individual honors contract required. Honors content noted on transcript. Letter grading.
LATIN 89HC.title: Honors Contracts

LATIN 99.description: Tutorial (supervised research or other scholarly work), three hours per week per unit. Entry-level research for lower division students under guidance of faculty mentor. Students must be in good academic standing and enrolled in minimum of 12 units (excluding this course). Individual contract required; consult Undergraduate Research Center. May be repeated. P/NP grading.
LATIN 99.title: Student Research Program
